following is a summary of the accidental release prevention program in place at Nebraska Energy LLC.  Because a process at the facility that is regulated by the Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA's) risk management program (RMP) regulation is also subject to the Occupational Safety and Health Administration's (OSHA's) process safety management (PSM) standard, this summary addresses each of the OSHA PSM elements and describes the management system in place to implement the accidental release prevention program.

EMPLOYEE PARTICIPATION

Involvement and participation by all employees and their representatives is an important aspect of Nebraska Energy?s PSM / RMP program.  Nebraska Energy LLC employee involvement in the PSM / RMP programs will ensure that all perspectives are considered and that the best ideas are implemented. In addition, all Nebraska Energy LLC employees have the right, and the responsibility, to participate in the development of PSM activities.

Nebraska Energy LLC will actively seek employee involvement through these basic approaches:

? By integrating PSM requirements into normal work activities;
? Through participation by interested employees on a voluntary basis;
? Through active consultation with all affected employees and their representatives;
? By addressing anonymous communication to any supervisor pertaining to any element of the PSM program;
? Through participation as subject matter experts in the development of operating procedures and training;
? Through participation on the PSM Committee;
? Participation in MOC meetings; and
? Participation in PHA studies.

PROCESS SAFETY INFORMATION

Nebraska Energy LLC has compiled written process safety information for all PSM covered processes.  The process safety information includes the hazards of chemicals used or produced in the process, process technology information, and process equipment data.  The process safety information is updated whenever process changes are made.

Accurate and c

omplete process safety information enables Nebraska Energy LLC employees involved in operating and maintaining the plant to identify and understand the hazards of the process.  Process safety information is used to conduct process hazard analysis on the existing process or a proposed modification to a process.

Nebraska Energy LLC process safety information is maintained in manuals available to all affected employees.  The Nebraska Energy LLC process safety information manuals contain the following information:

Material Safety Data Sheets (MSDS) for highly hazardous chemicals used in the process.

Information related to the technology of the process including the following:

? A process block flow diagram;
? Process chemistry;
? Maximum inventories of process vessels;
? Safe limits for process variables such as temperatures, pressures, levels, flows, and compositions; and
? Evaluation of the consequences of deviations from the safe limits for process variables.

Information regarding the equipment used in the process:

? Materials of construction;
? Piping and instrumentation diagrams;
? Electrical classification;
? Relief system design and design basis;
? Ventilation system design;
? Design codes and standards employed;
? Material and energy balances; and
? Safety systems including interlocks and fire suppression systems.


PROCESS HAZARD ANALYSIS (PHA)

Nebraska Energy is committed to performing a detailed hazard analysis of each covered process to identify, evaluate, and control hazards involved in the processes.  Each process is systematically examined to identify potential hazards controls in place to manage these hazards, and recommend additional controls, as appropriate.

Nebraska Energy LLC uses the hazard and operability (HAZOP) and check list PHA methodologies, which are conducted using a team of people who have operating and maintenance experience as well as engineering expertise.  The team identifies and evaluates potential hazards of the process as

 well as accident prevention and mitigation measures, and makes suggestions for additional prevention and / or mitigation measures. 

Whichever PHA methodology is used, the PHA addresses the following:

? The hazards of the process;
? Any previous process incident or near miss incident that could have resulted in a death, serious injury or large capital loss;
? Engineering and Administrative Controls used to reduce or eliminate process hazards;
? Consequences of failure of the Engineering and Administrative Controls;
? Facility Siting;
? Human Factors;
? A qualitative evaluation of possible safety and health effects on     employees in the workplace; and
? Potential offsite consequences (RMP requirement).

Nebraska Energy LLC periodically updates and revalidates the hazard analysis results.  As a minimum these periodic reviews are conducted every 5 years as long as the process is operating.

PHA finding and recommendations and the resolution of thereof are documented.  Nebraska Energy LLC has implemented a system to address and resolve all PHA findings and recommendations in a timely manner through a written schedule.  All PHA findings and recommendation resolutions are communicated to all effected employees.  All recommendations must be resolved by management.

OPERATING PROCEDURES

The policy of Nebraska Energy is to ensure that all operations covered under PSM have detailed procedures to cover each step of the process to assure that a ready and up to date reference is available and to form a foundation for needed employee training.  Operating procedures are readily accessible to employees who work in or maintain a process.

Nebraska Energy LLC operating procedures are reviewed as often as necessary to ensure that they reflect current operating practices, including changes in process chemicals, technology, equipment and facilities. To guard against outdated or inaccurate operating procedures, Nebraska Energy LLC certifies and documents annually that these operating

 procedures are current and accurate.

Nebraska Energy LLC written procedures address following phases of operation:
? Initial startup procedures;
? Normal operating procedures;
? Temporary operations;
? Emergency shutdown procedures;
? Emergency operations;
? Normal shutdown;
? Startup after a turnaround or emergency shutdown;
? Operating limits;
? Safety and health considerations; and
? Safety systems


TRAINING

Nebraska Energy believes that the implementation of an effective training program is one of the most important steps that an employer can take to enhance employee safety. Nebraska Energy LLC requires that each employee presently involved in operating a process or a newly assigned process must be trained in an overview of the process and in its operating procedures.  This training is done on initial hiring, when there are any changes in Nebraska Energy LLC operations and at least every three (3) years.  Nebraska Energy LLC training includes emphasis on the specific safety and health hazards of the process, emergency operations including shutdown, and other safe work practices that apply to the employee's job tasks.

Nebraska Energy LLC has clearly identified the employees to be trained, the subjects to be covered, and the goals and objectives to be achieved.  Nebraska Energy LLC has identified the important actions and conditions under which the employees will demonstrate competence or knowledge as well as what is acceptable performance.  Hands on training also enhances learning by teaching Nebraska Energy LLC employees under controlled conditions the correct operating procedures.

Nebraska Energy LLC periodically evaluates training programs to see if the necessary skills, knowledge, and routines are being properly understood and implemented by their trained employees.

CONTRACTORS

Nebraska Energy LLC uses contractors to supplement its workforce during periods of 
additional maintenance or construction activities.  Because some contractors work on or

near PSM covered process equipment, the facility has procedures in place to ensure that contractors:
? perform their work in a safe manner;
? have the appropriate knowledge and skills;
? are aware of the hazards in their workplace;
? understand what they should do in the event of an emergency;
? understand and follow site safety rules; and
? inform facility personnel of any hazards that they find during their work

Nebraska Energy LLC provides contractors with:
? a process overview;
? information about safety and health hazards;
? emergency response plan requirements; and
? safe work practices prior to their beginning work.

Nebraska Energy LLC evaluates contractor safety programs and performance during the selection of a contractor and throughout the contractors work activities.  Nebraska Energy LLC Facility personnel periodically monitor contractor performance with regard to their safety obligations.

PRE-STARTUP SAFETY REVIEWS (PSSR?s)

Nebraska Energy LLC requires a pre-startup safety review (PSSR) to be performed and documented for any physical modification in the PSM covered processes.  Additionally, any new units added at Nebraska Energy LLC which are considered PSM covered processes will also require a PSSR to be performed and documented.

Prior to the introduction of a highly hazardous chemical into a Nebraska Energy LLC PSM covered process, a pre startup safety review must confirm the following:
? Construction and equipment are in accordance with design specifications;
? Safety, operating, maintenance, and emergency procedures are in place and are adequate;
? A process hazard analysis has been performed for new or modified process and recommendations have been resolved or implemented before startup;
? A new or modified process meets the management of change requirements; and
? Training of each employee involved in operating a process has been completed.

